{"title_page": "Tejuca", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox ship begin <!-- full code -->\n|infobox caption= <!-- keywords: yes, nodab; or caption text -->\n|display title= ital <!-- keywords: none, ital; or article title with markup -->\n}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image= File:Rescue of the clipper Tejuca's crew by the ship Excelsior, 1856.jpg \n|Ship image size=\n|Ship caption= Rescue of ''Tejuca''{{'}}s crew by ''Excelsior'' (right), 1856 \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=\n|Ship flag=\n|Ship name= '''''Tejuca''''' \n|Ship namesake= [[Tijuca]], [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil \n|Ship owner= Napier, Johnson & Co. \n|Ship operator= \n|Ship registry=\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder= [[Isaac C. Smith|Isaac C. Smith & Son]] ([[Hoboken, New Jersey|Hoboken, NY]]) \n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched= 24 May 1854 \n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship recommissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship maiden voyage= 15 June 1854 \n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship refit=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship honors=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate= Sunk by hurricane in mid-[[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]], 5 January 1856 \n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship type= [[Clipper ship]] \n|Ship tonnage= 470 tons \n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship tons burthen=\n|Ship length= {{convert|140|ft|m|abbr=on}} \n|Ship beam= {{convert|28|ft|m|abbr=on}} \n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship draft=\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship hold depth= {{convert|12|ft|m|abbr=on}} \n|Ship decks=\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion= Sail \n|Ship sail plan= [[Full-rigged ship|Square rigged]] \n|Ship speed=\n|Ship crew= 17 \n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''''Tejuca''''' was a small 470-ton [[clipper ship]] built in [[Hoboken, New Jersey]] in 1854. After only eighteen months of service, she was lost in a hurricane on the North Atlantic, with most of her crew rescued through a daring maneuver carried out by the ship ''Excelsior''.\n\nBuilt for South American service, ''Tejuca'' spent most of her brief career in the coffee trade between Brazil and the United States, making four round trips between the two countries, including a passage between [[Bahia]] and [[New Orleans]] in early 1855 that at the time was reportedly one of the fastest on record. \n\nIn late December 1855, ''Tejuca'' embarked on her first [[transatlantic crossing]], and a few days later ran into a severe hurricane. With the ship badly damaged and in a sinking condition, all but one of her crew were rescued by the ship ''Excelsior'', whose captain risked his own vessel by bringing it alongside ''Tejuca'' while the storm still raged. ''Excelsior''{{'}}s captain later received an award for gallantry for the rescue. \n\n== Construction and design ==\n\n''Tejuca'', a wood-[[hull (watercraft)|hulled]] clipper ship,{{efn|Lindsey refers to ''Tejuca'' as a [[barque|bark]],<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/> a description repeated by Knoblock,<ref name=knoblock2014_p347/> but all contemporaneous sources describe her as a ship (see References section below) and the sole illustration of the vessel&mdash;the painting by Thomas Pitman (see above)&mdash;shows her to be ship-rigged.}} was built in 1854 by [[Isaac C. Smith|Isaac C. Smith & Son]] of Hoboken, New Jersey, for Napier, Johnson & Co., a New York firm.<ref name=nyherald_29jun1854>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Isaac C. Smith and Son |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/15304423/isaac_c_smith_1854_launches_to_jun/ |work= The New York Herald |date= 1854-06-29 |page= 2 |via= [[Newspapers.com]]|access-date= }}{{open access}}</ref><ref name=nyherald_24may1854/> Launched 24 May 1854, ''Tejuca'' was built \"for the South American trade\",<ref name=nytribune_20may1854/>{{efn|<ref name=nyherald_24may1854>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Marine Affairs |url= https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030313/1854-05-24/ed-1/seq-4/#date1=1789&sort=relevance&rows=20&words=C+Isaac+Smith&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=3&state=New+York&date2=1943&proxtext=%22isaac+c.+smith%22&y=12&x=12&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1 |work= The New York Herald |date= 1854-05-24 |page= 4 |access-date= }}</ref> The source erroneously refers to the ship as ''Tejorca''.}} and was named after the district of [[Tijuca]]{{efn|Commonly spelled \"Tejuca\" in the 19th century.<ref name=francis1840_p149>Francis 1840. '''I'''. p. [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Xs28_XlfvrEC&pg=PA149&dq=tejuca&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjw7J_5vPvcAhUQFnwKHfIeB6AQ6AEIbzAN#v=onepage&q=tejuca&f=false 149].</ref>}} in [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil, then known for its coffee plantations.<ref name=francis1840_p149/><ref name=galeano1997_p97>Galeano 1997. p. [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=XPFzV9VRFuEC&pg=PA97&dq=tijuca+brazil+coffee&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiT4Pbmh5zcAhVIULwKHdN1AZIQ6AEITTAH#v=onepage&q=tijuca%20brazil%20coffee&f=false 97].</ref> \n\n''Tejuca'' was {{convert|140|ft|m}} in length, with a beam of {{convert|28|ft}} and hold depth of {{convert|12|ft}}.<ref name=nyherald_24may1854/> Her carrying capacity was 470 tons,<ref name=knoblock2014_p347>Knoblock 2014. p. 347.</ref><ref name=nyherald_29jun1854/> and she had some accommodation for passengers. At time of launch, she was described in newspaper reports as a \"finely modelled\"<ref name=nyherald_24may1854/> and \"finely proportioned\"<ref name=nytribune_20may1854>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Ship Launch |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201854%20May%20-%20Aug%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201854%20May%20-%20Aug%20Grayscale%20-%200142.pdf |work= New York Tribune |date= 1854-05-20 |page= 5 }}</ref> ship that combined \"carrying capacity with qualities for sailing.\"<ref name=nyherald_24may1854/><ref name=nytribune_20may1854/> \n\n''Tejuca'' was to be commanded for the whole of her brief career by William D. Gregory.<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/> Her New York agent was Gurdon S. Coit of 106 Wall Street, who was also agent for the clipper ''Sunny South'', skippered by Gregory{{'}}s brother Michael.<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69>Lindsey 1915. pp. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015047402535?urlappend=%3Bseq=78 68&ndash;69].</ref>\n\n== Service history ==\n\n''Tejuca'' made a total of four round trips between the United States and Brazil from June 1854 to December 1855, usually calling at [[Rio de Janeiro]] via [[Bahia]] and returning via Bahia to New York, although one return voyage was made to [[New Orleans]]. The return cargo on the first three trips was coffee, but the last was made with a cargo of sugar. ''Tejuca''{{'}}s coffee cargoes typically attracted good prices in the United States as Brazilian coffee was much in demand at this time.<ref name=sw_courier&enquirer_8sep1855/> The ship{{'}}s outbound cargoes are not known. \n\n''Tejuca'' departed New York on her maiden voyage June 15 1854,<ref name=nytribune_16jun1854>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Marine Journal |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201854%20May%20-%20Aug%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201854%20May%20-%20Aug%20Grayscale%20-%200329.pdf |work= New York Tribune |date= 1854-06-16 |page= 8 }}</ref> bound for Rio via Bahia, returning to New York 14 October with two passengers<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Personal Intelligence |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2014/New%20York%20NY%20Herald/New%20York%20NY%20Herald%201854/New%20York%20NY%20Herald%201854%20-%202237.pdf |work= The New York Herald |date= 1854-10-15 |page= 4 }}</ref> and a consignment of 5,000 bags of coffee for Napier, Johnson & Co.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Shipping Intelligence |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2010/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Post/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Post%201854%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Post%201854%20Grayscale%20-%201073.pdf |work= The Evening Post |location= New York |date= 1854-10-16 |page= 3 }}</ref> Clearing New York 18 November, ''Tejuca'' made a second passage to Rio via Bahia.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Maritime Intelligence |url= https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030313/1854-11-19/ed-1/seq-8/#date1=1789&sort=date&date2=1943&words=Ship+Tejuca&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=5&state=&rows=20&proxtext=%22ship+tejuca%22&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1 |work= The New York Herald |date= 1854-11-19 |page= 8 }}</ref> Departing Rio 5 February, the vessel then completed \"one of the quickest passages on record\"<ref name=picayune_14mar1855>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= No title |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/15516423/tejuca_fast_passage_early_1855/ |work= The Daily Picayune |location= New Orleans |date= 1855-03-14 |page= 2 |via= [[Newspapers.com]] }}{{Open access}}</ref> between that port and [[New Orleans]], where she arrived 14 March with a cargo of 4,541 bags of coffee.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Imports by Sea |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/22488192/tejuca_coffee_to_no_mar_1855/ |work= New Orleans Price-Current, Commercial Intelligencer and Merchants{{'}} Transcript |date= 1855-03-14 |page= 3 |via= [[Newspapers.com]] |access-date= }}{{Open access}}</ref>  \n\nFrom New Orleans, ''Tejuca'' returned for a third time to Rio, departing 25 April<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Home Ports |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/22488631/tejuca_leaves_no_for_rio_apr_25_1855/ |work= The New York Herald |date= 1855-05-03 |page= 8 |via= [[Newspapers.com]] |access-date= }}{{Open access}}</ref> and arriving 7 July,<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Foreign Ports |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2018/New%20York%20NY%20Morning%20Courier/New%20York%20NY%20Morning%20Courier%201855/New%20York%20NY%20Morning%20Courier%201855%20-%201563.pdf |work= Morning Courier and New-York Enquirer |date= 1855-08-16 |page= 3 }}</ref> before returning via New Orleans to New York, where she arrived early September with 4,834 bags of coffee.<ref name=sw_courier&enquirer_8sep1855>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Wednesday Evening, Sept. 5 |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2011/New%20York%20NY%20Semi-Weekly%20Courier%20and%20Enquirer/New%20York%20NY%20Semi-Weekly%20Courier%20and%20Enquirer%201855-1856%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Semi-Weekly%20Courier%20and%20Enquirer%201855-1856%20Grayscale%20-%200159.pdf |work= Semi-Weekly Courier and New-York Enquirer |date= 1855-09-08 |page= 4 }}</ref> ''Tejuca''{{'}}s final voyage to Brazil was again made to Rio<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= For South American Ports |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2018/New%20York%20NY%20Morning%20Courier/New%20York%20NY%20Morning%20Courier%201855/New%20York%20NY%20Morning%20Courier%201855%20-%201724.pdf |work= Morning Courier and New-York Enquirer |date= 1855-09-08 |page= 4 }}</ref> via Bahia, clearing New York 10 September<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Marine Journal |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/22489576/tejuca_clears_ny_for_bahia_10_sep_1855/ |work= New York Tribune |date= 1855-09-11 |page= 8 |via= [[Newspapers.com]] |access-date= }}{{Open access}}</ref> and returning 14 December with a cargo of sugar.<ref name=nytribune_15dec1855/> On the latter voyage, the ship experienced heavy weather, losing her [[Glossary of nautical terms#topgallant|topgallant mast]] and having several [[Glossary of nautical terms#yard|yards]] sprung and sails split, while also being \"twice blown off the coast.\"<ref name=nytribune_15dec1855>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Arrived |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201855%20Sep%20-Dec%20Grayscale/New%20York%20%20NY%20Tribune%201855%20Sep%20-Dec%20Grayscale%20-%200735.pdf |work= New York Tribune |date= 1855-12-15 |page= 8 }}</ref> \n\n=== Loss ===\n\n''Tejuca''{{'}}s first attempt at a [[transatlantic crossing]] was fated to become her final voyage. On 27 December 1855, the ship departed New York for [[Cobh|Queenstown]], Ireland, with a cargo of sugar. The first few days of the voyage were uneventful, but on the night of 4 January, the ship ran into a \"tremendous gale\".<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/> The following morning, the vessel shipped a sea that damaged the front of the [[poop deck]], allowing water into the hold. After nightfall, the gale developed into a \"terrible hurricane\",<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/> and at midnight, ''Tejuca'' shipped another sea which rolled the ship almost on her [[Glossary of nautical terms#beam ends|beam ends]], broke most of the yards and destroyed or swept away everything on deck including the lifeboats, the seawater also contaminating the crew{{'}}s food stores and drinking water.<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/> \n\nBy the 7th, without provisions<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/> and with waves broaching over the deck and the ship \"nearly on a level with the water and settling fast\",<ref name=nyherald_25feb1856>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Miscellaneous and Disasters |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/22303657/rescue_of_tejucas_crew_gregorys/ |work= The New York Herald |date= 1856-02-25 |page= 8 |via= [[Newspapers.com]] |access-date= }}{{Open access}}</ref> captain and crew had given up hope of survival when, at about 1 pm, a sail appeared on the horizon, belonging to the ship ''Excelsior''&mdash;a small merchant vessel of about the same tonnage as ''Tejuca''.<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/><ref name=nyherald_25feb1856/> ''Excelsior''{{'}}s captain, Eben Mitchell of [[Kennebunk, Maine]], had seen ''Tejuca''{{'}}s plight and determined to aid her crew, in spite of his own vessel having itself taken a severe battering from the hurricane.<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/><ref name=nyherald_25feb1856/> \n\nWhen within range, Mitchell first attempted to launch one or more of his ship{{'}}s lifeboats, but these were either swamped or dashed against the side of his ship and destroyed:<ref name=dailypicayune_10jun1856/> \n<blockquote>Nothing then remained for the doomed crew save the desperate expedient of placing the ships alongside. Calling his men aft, [Mitchell] addressed them in the eloquence of earnestness; he pointed out the peril, but he showed them the hope! A hearty cheer told him the gallant fellows would go wherever he led; for the slightest collision in that raging storm must have been fatal to both.<ref name=dailypicayune_10jun1856>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= A Well Deserved Testimonial |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/15516405/tejuca_rescue_1855_testimonial/ |work= The Daily Picayune |location= New Orleans |date= 1856-06-10 |page= 3? |via= [[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nMitchell, \"skilfully watching the lift and fall\" of the waves,<ref name=dailypicayune_10jun1856/> brought his vessel alongside ''Tejuca''{{'}}s bow and had his crew throw lines to the stricken vessel, by means of which some of ''Tejuca''{{'}}s crew were hauled aboard.<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/> The two ships then came together closely enough for the remaining crew to leap to the safety of ''Excelsior''{{'}}s [[Glossary of nautical terms#chain-wale or channel|channels]],<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/> whereupon Mitchell signalled a contingent of his crew&mdash;standing by for the purpose&mdash;to unfurl the foresail, drawing ''Excelsior'' out of danger.<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/> All of ''Tejuca''{{'}}s crew were saved in the operation but one, who lost his footing and was crushed between the two ships; though he too was hauled aboard ''Excelsior'', he died a few hours later from internal injuries.<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/><ref name=dailypicayune_10jun1856/>\n\n=== Aftermath === \n\nAfter the rescue, ''Excelsior'' continued on to her destination  of [[Le Havre]], France, where she limped into port on 20 January \"almost a wreck herself\".<ref name=nytribune_27feb1856>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Disasters, &c |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201856%20Jan%20-%20Apr%20Grayscale/New%20York%20%20NY%20Tribune%201856%20Jan%20-%20Apr%20Grayscale%20-%200396.pdf |work= New York Tribune |date= 1856-02-27 |page= 8 }}</ref> Captain Gregory later gave accounts of the rescue to the newspapers, in which he expressed his profound gratitude to Captain Mitchell, his officers and crew for their \"noble, perilous and successful exertions\" in effecting the rescue and their \"humane and benevolent conduct\" thereafter.<ref name=nytribune_2apr1856>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Disasters, &c |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201856%20Jan%20-%20Apr%20Grayscale/New%20York%20%20NY%20Tribune%201856%20Jan%20-%20Apr%20Grayscale%20-%200640.pdf |work= New York Tribune |date= 1856-04-02 |page= 8 }}</ref> The following May, a group of shipmasters from [[Mobile, Alabama]], presented Captain Mitchell with a \"handsome service of plate ... as a testimonial of their appreciation of his gallant conduct in rescuing the crew and officers of the clipper ship ''Tejuca''\".<ref name=dailypicayune_10jun1856/> \n\nThe loss of ''Tejuca'' and her cargo was estimated at $80,000 ({{inflation|US|80,000|1856|fmt=eq}}).<ref name=insurancegazette/> ''Tejuca'' was one of 79 American ships lost and over a thousand damaged in the first six months of 1856, described at the time as \"a period probably without parallel in our commercial history\",<ref name=insurancegazette/> with total losses estimated at $15,890,500 ({{inflation|US|15,890,500|1856|fmt=eq}}).<ref name=insurancegazette>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Six Months with the Underwriters; or, the Marine Disasters Reported from the 1st of January to 1st July, 1856 |url= https://hdl.handle.net/2027/chi.52054105?urlappend=%3Bseq=246 |magazine= The United States Insurance Gazette and Magazine of Useful Knowledge |location= New York |publisher= G. E. Currie |date= August 1856 |volume= 3 |issue= 16 |pages= 228&ndash;235 |access-date= }}</ref>\n\n== Footnotes == \n{{notelist}}\n\n== References == \n{{Reflist|30em}} \n=== Bibliography === \n{{refbegin|3|normalfont=yes}} \n;Books \n* {{cite book |last= Francis |first= Charles S. |date= 1840 |title= Around the World: A Narrative of a Voyage in the East India Squadron, Under Commodore George C. Read by an Officer of the U. S. Navy |volume= I |location= Boston |publisher= Joseph H. Francis |page= [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Xs28_XlfvrEC&pg=PA149&dq=tejuca&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjw7J_5vPvcAhUQFnwKHfIeB6AQ6AEIbzAN#v=onepage&q=tejuca&f=false 149] }} \n* {{cite book |last= Galeano |first= Eduardo |date= 1997 |title= Open Veins of Latin America: Five Centuries of the Pillage of a Continent |location= |publisher= NYU Press |page= [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=XPFzV9VRFuEC&pg=PA97&dq=tijuca+brazil+coffee&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiT4Pbmh5zcAhVIULwKHdN1AZIQ6AEITTAH#v=onepage&q=tijuca%20brazil%20coffee&f=false 97] |isbn= 9781583673119 |author-link= }} \n* {{cite book |last= Knoblock |first= Glenn A. |date= 2014 |title= The American Clipper Ship, 1845&ndash;1920 |location= Jefferson, NC |publisher= McFarland & Company, Inc |page= 347 |isbn= 978-0-7864-7112-6 |author-link= }}\n* {{cite book |last= Lindsey |first= Benjamin J. |date= 1915 |title= Old Marblehead Sea Captains and the Ships in Which They Sailed |location= Marblehead, MA |publisher= Marblehead Historical Society |pages= [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015047402535?urlappend=%3Bseq=78 68&ndash;69] |author-link= }}\n;Newspapers and magazines \n* ''[[The New York Herald]]'' \n* ''[[New York Tribune]]'' \n* ''[[The Evening Post]]'' (New York) \n* ''[[The Times-Picayune|The Daily Picayune]]'' ([[New Orleans]]) \n* ''[[New Orleans Price-Current, Commercial Intelligencer and Merchants' Transcript]]'' \n* ''[[Morning Courier and New-York Enquirer]]'' \n* ''[[Semi-Weekly Courier and New-York Enquirer]]'' \n* ''The United States Insurance Gazette and Magazine of Useful Knowledge'' \n; Archival websites \n* [[Fultonhistory.com]] \n* [[Hathitrust|Hathitrust Digital Library]] \n* [[Newspapers.com]] \n\n{{refend}} \n\n[[Category:1854 ships]] \n[[Category:Ships built by Isaac C. Smith]] \n[[Category:Ships built in Hoboken, New Jersey]] \n[[Category:Clipper ships built in the United States]] \n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1856]]\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin <!-- full code -->\n|infobox caption= <!-- keywords: yes, nodab; or caption text -->\n|display title= ital <!-- keywords: none, ital; or article title with markup -->\n}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image= File:Rescue of the clipper Tejuca's crew by the ship Excelsior, 1856.jpg \n|Ship image size=\n|Ship caption= Rescue of ''Tejuca''{{'}}s crew by ''Excelsior'' (right), 1856 \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=\n|Ship flag=\n|Ship name= '''''Tejuca''''' \n|Ship namesake= [[Tijuca]], [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil \n|Ship owner= Napier, Johnson & Co. \n|Ship operator= \n|Ship registry=\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder= [[Isaac C. Smith|Isaac C. Smith & Son]] ([[Hoboken, New Jersey|Hoboken, NY]]) \n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched= 24 May 1854 \n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship recommissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship maiden voyage= 15 June 1854 \n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship refit=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship honors=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate= Sunk by hurricane in mid-[[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]], 5 January 1856 \n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship type= [[Clipper ship]] \n|Ship tonnage= 470 tons \n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship tons burthen=\n|Ship length= {{convert|140|ft|m|abbr=on}} \n|Ship beam= {{convert|28|ft|m|abbr=on}} \n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship draft=\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship hold depth= {{convert|12|ft|m|abbr=on}} \n|Ship decks=\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion= Sail \n|Ship sail plan= [[Full-rigged ship|Square rigged]] \n|Ship speed=\n|Ship crew= 17 \n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''''Tejuca''''' was a small 470-ton [[clipper ship]] built in [[Hoboken, New Jersey]] in 1854. After only eighteen months of service, she was lost in a hurricane on the North Atlantic, with most of her crew rescued through a daring maneuver carried out by the ship ''Excelsior''.\n\nBuilt for South American service, ''Tejuca'' spent most of her brief career in the coffee trade between Brazil and the United States, making four round trips between the two countries, including a passage between [[Bahia]] and [[New Orleans]] in early 1855 that at the time was reportedly one of the fastest on record. \n\nIn late December 1855, ''Tejuca'' embarked on her first [[transatlantic crossing]], and a few days later ran into a severe hurricane. With the ship badly damaged and in a sinking condition, all but one of her crew were rescued by the ship ''Excelsior'', whose captain risked his own vessel by bringing it alongside ''Tejuca'' while the storm still raged. ''Excelsior''{{'}}s captain later received an award for gallantry for the rescue. \n\n== Construction and design ==\n\n''Tejuca'', a wood-[[hull (watercraft)|hulled]] clipper ship,{{efn|Lindsey refers to ''Tejuca'' as a [[barque|bark]],<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/> a description repeated by Knoblock,<ref name=knoblock2014_p347/> but all contemporaneous sources describe her as a ship (see References section below) and the sole illustration of the vessel&mdash;the painting by Thomas Pitman (see above)&mdash;shows her to be ship-rigged.}} was built in 1854 by [[Isaac C. Smith|Isaac C. Smith & Son]] of Hoboken, New Jersey, for Napier, Johnson & Co., a New York firm.<ref name=nyherald_29jun1854>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Isaac C. Smith and Son |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/15304423/isaac_c_smith_1854_launches_to_jun/ |work= The New York Herald |date= 1854-06-29 |page= 2 |via= [[Newspapers.com]]|access-date= }}{{open access}}</ref><ref name=nyherald_24may1854/> Launched 24 May 1854, ''Tejuca'' was built \"for the South American trade\",<ref name=nytribune_20may1854/>{{efn|<ref name=nyherald_24may1854>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Marine Affairs |url= https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030313/1854-05-24/ed-1/seq-4/#date1=1789&sort=relevance&rows=20&words=C+Isaac+Smith&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=3&state=New+York&date2=1943&proxtext=%22isaac+c.+smith%22&y=12&x=12&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1 |work= The New York Herald |date= 1854-05-24 |page= 4 |access-date= }}</ref> The source erroneously refers to the ship as ''Tejorca''.}} and was named after the district of [[Tijuca]]{{efn|Commonly spelled \"Tejuca\" in the 19th century.<ref name=francis1840_p149>Francis 1840. '''I'''. p. [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Xs28_XlfvrEC&pg=PA149&dq=tejuca&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjw7J_5vPvcAhUQFnwKHfIeB6AQ6AEIbzAN#v=onepage&q=tejuca&f=false 149].</ref>}} in [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil, then known for its coffee plantations.<ref name=francis1840_p149/><ref name=galeano1997_p97>Galeano 1997. p. [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=XPFzV9VRFuEC&pg=PA97&dq=tijuca+brazil+coffee&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiT4Pbmh5zcAhVIULwKHdN1AZIQ6AEITTAH#v=onepage&q=tijuca%20brazil%20coffee&f=false 97].</ref> \n\n''Tejuca'' was {{convert|140|ft|m}} in length, with a beam of {{convert|28|ft}} and hold depth of {{convert|12|ft}}.<ref name=nyherald_24may1854/> Her carrying capacity was 470 tons,<ref name=knoblock2014_p347>Knoblock 2014. p. 347.</ref><ref name=nyherald_29jun1854/> and she had some accommodation for passengers. At time of launch, she was described in newspaper reports as a \"finely modelled\"<ref name=nyherald_24may1854/> and \"finely proportioned\"<ref name=nytribune_20may1854>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Ship Launch |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201854%20May%20-%20Aug%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201854%20May%20-%20Aug%20Grayscale%20-%200142.pdf |work= New York Tribune |date= 1854-05-20 |page= 5 }}</ref> ship that combined \"carrying capacity with qualities for sailing.\"<ref name=nyherald_24may1854/><ref name=nytribune_20may1854/> \n\n''Tejuca'' was to be commanded for the whole of her brief career by [[William D. Gregory]].<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/> Her New York agent was Gurdon S. Coit of 106 Wall Street, who was also agent for the clipper ''Sunny South'', skippered by Gregory{{'}}s brother Michael.<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69>Lindsey 1915. pp. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015047402535?urlappend=%3Bseq=78 68&ndash;69].</ref>\n\n== Service history ==\n\n''Tejuca'' made a total of four round trips between the United States and Brazil from June 1854 to December 1855, usually calling at [[Rio de Janeiro]] via [[Bahia]] and returning via Bahia to New York, although one return voyage was made to [[New Orleans]]. The return cargo on the first three trips was coffee, but the last was made with a cargo of sugar. ''Tejuca''{{'}}s coffee cargoes typically attracted good prices in the United States as Brazilian coffee was much in demand at this time.<ref name=sw_courier&enquirer_8sep1855/> The ship{{'}}s outbound cargoes are not known. \n\n''Tejuca'' departed New York on her maiden voyage June 15 1854,<ref name=nytribune_16jun1854>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Marine Journal |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201854%20May%20-%20Aug%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201854%20May%20-%20Aug%20Grayscale%20-%200329.pdf |work= New York Tribune |date= 1854-06-16 |page= 8 }}</ref> bound for Rio via Bahia, returning to New York 14 October with two passengers<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Personal Intelligence |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2014/New%20York%20NY%20Herald/New%20York%20NY%20Herald%201854/New%20York%20NY%20Herald%201854%20-%202237.pdf |work= The New York Herald |date= 1854-10-15 |page= 4 }}</ref> and a consignment of 5,000 bags of coffee for Napier, Johnson & Co.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Shipping Intelligence |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2010/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Post/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Post%201854%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Post%201854%20Grayscale%20-%201073.pdf |work= The Evening Post |location= New York |date= 1854-10-16 |page= 3 }}</ref> Clearing New York 18 November, ''Tejuca'' made a second passage to Rio via Bahia.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Maritime Intelligence |url= https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030313/1854-11-19/ed-1/seq-8/#date1=1789&sort=date&date2=1943&words=Ship+Tejuca&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=5&state=&rows=20&proxtext=%22ship+tejuca%22&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1 |work= The New York Herald |date= 1854-11-19 |page= 8 }}</ref> Departing Rio 5 February, the vessel then completed \"one of the quickest passages on record\"<ref name=picayune_14mar1855>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= No title |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/15516423/tejuca_fast_passage_early_1855/ |work= The Daily Picayune |location= New Orleans |date= 1855-03-14 |page= 2 |via= [[Newspapers.com]] }}{{Open access}}</ref> between that port and [[New Orleans]], where she arrived 14 March with a cargo of 4,541 bags of coffee.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Imports by Sea |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/22488192/tejuca_coffee_to_no_mar_1855/ |work= New Orleans Price-Current, Commercial Intelligencer and Merchants{{'}} Transcript |date= 1855-03-14 |page= 3 |via= [[Newspapers.com]] |access-date= }}{{Open access}}</ref>  \n\nFrom New Orleans, ''Tejuca'' returned for a third time to Rio, departing 25 April<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Home Ports |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/22488631/tejuca_leaves_no_for_rio_apr_25_1855/ |work= The New York Herald |date= 1855-05-03 |page= 8 |via= [[Newspapers.com]] |access-date= }}{{Open access}}</ref> and arriving 7 July,<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Foreign Ports |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2018/New%20York%20NY%20Morning%20Courier/New%20York%20NY%20Morning%20Courier%201855/New%20York%20NY%20Morning%20Courier%201855%20-%201563.pdf |work= Morning Courier and New-York Enquirer |date= 1855-08-16 |page= 3 }}</ref> before returning via New Orleans to New York, where she arrived early September with 4,834 bags of coffee.<ref name=sw_courier&enquirer_8sep1855>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Wednesday Evening, Sept. 5 |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2011/New%20York%20NY%20Semi-Weekly%20Courier%20and%20Enquirer/New%20York%20NY%20Semi-Weekly%20Courier%20and%20Enquirer%201855-1856%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Semi-Weekly%20Courier%20and%20Enquirer%201855-1856%20Grayscale%20-%200159.pdf |work= Semi-Weekly Courier and New-York Enquirer |date= 1855-09-08 |page= 4 }}</ref> ''Tejuca''{{'}}s final voyage to Brazil was again made to Rio<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= For South American Ports |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2018/New%20York%20NY%20Morning%20Courier/New%20York%20NY%20Morning%20Courier%201855/New%20York%20NY%20Morning%20Courier%201855%20-%201724.pdf |work= Morning Courier and New-York Enquirer |date= 1855-09-08 |page= 4 }}</ref> via Bahia, clearing New York 10 September<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Marine Journal |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/22489576/tejuca_clears_ny_for_bahia_10_sep_1855/ |work= New York Tribune |date= 1855-09-11 |page= 8 |via= [[Newspapers.com]] |access-date= }}{{Open access}}</ref> and returning 14 December with a cargo of sugar.<ref name=nytribune_15dec1855/> On the latter voyage, the ship experienced heavy weather, losing her [[Glossary of nautical terms#topgallant|topgallant mast]] and having several [[Glossary of nautical terms#yard|yards]] sprung and sails split, while also being \"twice blown off the coast.\"<ref name=nytribune_15dec1855>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Arrived |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201855%20Sep%20-Dec%20Grayscale/New%20York%20%20NY%20Tribune%201855%20Sep%20-Dec%20Grayscale%20-%200735.pdf |work= New York Tribune |date= 1855-12-15 |page= 8 }}</ref> \n\n=== Loss ===\n\n''Tejuca''{{'}}s first attempt at a [[transatlantic crossing]] was fated to become her final voyage. On 27 December 1855, the ship departed New York for [[Cobh|Queenstown]], Ireland, with a cargo of sugar. The first few days of the voyage were uneventful, but on the night of 4 January, the ship ran into a \"tremendous gale\".<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/> The following morning, the vessel shipped a sea that damaged the front of the [[poop deck]], allowing water into the hold. After nightfall, the gale developed into a \"terrible hurricane\",<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/> and at midnight, ''Tejuca'' shipped another sea which rolled the ship almost on her [[Glossary of nautical terms#beam ends|beam ends]], broke most of the yards and destroyed or swept away everything on deck including the lifeboats, the seawater also contaminating the crew{{'}}s food stores and drinking water.<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/> \n\nBy the 7th, without provisions<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/> and with waves broaching over the deck and the ship \"nearly on a level with the water and settling fast\",<ref name=nyherald_25feb1856>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Miscellaneous and Disasters |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/22303657/rescue_of_tejucas_crew_gregorys/ |work= The New York Herald |date= 1856-02-25 |page= 8 |via= [[Newspapers.com]] |access-date= }}{{Open access}}</ref> captain and crew had given up hope of survival when, at about 1 pm, a sail appeared on the horizon, belonging to the ship ''Excelsior''&mdash;a small merchant vessel of about the same tonnage as ''Tejuca''.<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/><ref name=nyherald_25feb1856/> ''Excelsior''{{'}}s captain, Eben Mitchell of [[Kennebunk, Maine]], had seen ''Tejuca''{{'}}s plight and determined to aid her crew, in spite of his own vessel having itself taken a severe battering from the hurricane.<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/><ref name=nyherald_25feb1856/> \n\nWhen within range, Mitchell first attempted to launch one or more of his ship{{'}}s lifeboats, but these were either swamped or dashed against the side of his ship and destroyed:<ref name=dailypicayune_10jun1856/> \n<blockquote>Nothing then remained for the doomed crew save the desperate expedient of placing the ships alongside. Calling his men aft, [Mitchell] addressed them in the eloquence of earnestness; he pointed out the peril, but he showed them the hope! A hearty cheer told him the gallant fellows would go wherever he led; for the slightest collision in that raging storm must have been fatal to both.<ref name=dailypicayune_10jun1856>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= A Well Deserved Testimonial |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/15516405/tejuca_rescue_1855_testimonial/ |work= The Daily Picayune |location= New Orleans |date= 1856-06-10 |page= 3? |via= [[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nMitchell, \"skilfully watching the lift and fall\" of the waves,<ref name=dailypicayune_10jun1856/> brought his vessel alongside ''Tejuca''{{'}}s bow and had his crew throw lines to the stricken vessel, by means of which some of ''Tejuca''{{'}}s crew were hauled aboard.<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/> The two ships then came together closely enough for the remaining crew to leap to the safety of ''Excelsior''{{'}}s [[Glossary of nautical terms#chain-wale or channel|channels]],<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/> whereupon Mitchell signalled a contingent of his crew&mdash;standing by for the purpose&mdash;to unfurl the foresail, drawing ''Excelsior'' out of danger.<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/> All of ''Tejuca''{{'}}s crew were saved in the operation but one, who lost his footing and was crushed between the two ships; though he too was hauled aboard ''Excelsior'', he died a few hours later from internal injuries.<ref name=lindsey1915_pp68-69/><ref name=dailypicayune_10jun1856/>\n\n=== Aftermath === \n\nAfter the rescue, ''Excelsior'' continued on to her destination  of [[Le Havre]], France, where she limped into port on 20 January \"almost a wreck herself\".<ref name=nytribune_27feb1856>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Disasters, &c |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201856%20Jan%20-%20Apr%20Grayscale/New%20York%20%20NY%20Tribune%201856%20Jan%20-%20Apr%20Grayscale%20-%200396.pdf |work= New York Tribune |date= 1856-02-27 |page= 8 }}</ref> Captain Gregory later gave accounts of the rescue to the newspapers, in which he expressed his profound gratitude to Captain Mitchell, his officers and crew for their \"noble, perilous and successful exertions\" in effecting the rescue and their \"humane and benevolent conduct\" thereafter.<ref name=nytribune_2apr1856>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Disasters, &c |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201856%20Jan%20-%20Apr%20Grayscale/New%20York%20%20NY%20Tribune%201856%20Jan%20-%20Apr%20Grayscale%20-%200640.pdf |work= New York Tribune |date= 1856-04-02 |page= 8 }}</ref> The following May, a group of shipmasters from [[Mobile, Alabama]], presented Captain Mitchell with a \"handsome service of plate ... as a testimonial of their appreciation of his gallant conduct in rescuing the crew and officers of the clipper ship ''Tejuca''\".<ref name=dailypicayune_10jun1856/> \n\nThe loss of ''Tejuca'' and her cargo was estimated at $80,000 ({{inflation|US|80,000|1856|fmt=eq}}).<ref name=insurancegazette/> ''Tejuca'' was one of 79 American ships lost and over a thousand damaged in the first six months of 1856, described at the time as \"a period probably without parallel in our commercial history\",<ref name=insurancegazette/> with total losses estimated at $15,890,500 ({{inflation|US|15,890,500|1856|fmt=eq}}).<ref name=insurancegazette>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Six Months with the Underwriters; or, the Marine Disasters Reported from the 1st of January to 1st July, 1856 |url= https://hdl.handle.net/2027/chi.52054105?urlappend=%3Bseq=246 |magazine= The United States Insurance Gazette and Magazine of Useful Knowledge |location= New York |publisher= G. E. Currie |date= August 1856 |volume= 3 |issue= 16 |pages= 228&ndash;235 |access-date= }}</ref>\n\n== Footnotes == \n{{notelist}}\n\n== References == \n{{Reflist|30em}} \n=== Bibliography === \n{{refbegin|3|normalfont=yes}} \n;Books \n* {{cite book |last= Francis |first= Charles S. |date= 1840 |title= Around the World: A Narrative of a Voyage in the East India Squadron, Under Commodore George C. Read by an Officer of the U. S. Navy |volume= I |location= Boston |publisher= Joseph H. Francis |page= [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Xs28_XlfvrEC&pg=PA149&dq=tejuca&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjw7J_5vPvcAhUQFnwKHfIeB6AQ6AEIbzAN#v=onepage&q=tejuca&f=false 149] }} \n* {{cite book |last= Galeano |first= Eduardo |date= 1997 |title= Open Veins of Latin America: Five Centuries of the Pillage of a Continent |location= |publisher= NYU Press |page= [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=XPFzV9VRFuEC&pg=PA97&dq=tijuca+brazil+coffee&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiT4Pbmh5zcAhVIULwKHdN1AZIQ6AEITTAH#v=onepage&q=tijuca%20brazil%20coffee&f=false 97] |isbn= 9781583673119 |author-link= }} \n* {{cite book |last= Knoblock |first= Glenn A. |date= 2014 |title= The American Clipper Ship, 1845&ndash;1920 |location= Jefferson, NC |publisher= McFarland & Company, Inc |page= 347 |isbn= 978-0-7864-7112-6 |author-link= }}\n* {{cite book |last= Lindsey |first= Benjamin J. |date= 1915 |title= Old Marblehead Sea Captains and the Ships in Which They Sailed |location= Marblehead, MA |publisher= Marblehead Historical Society |pages= [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015047402535?urlappend=%3Bseq=78 68&ndash;69] |author-link= }}\n;Newspapers and magazine