h American Footballer of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Albania]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Venezuela]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{spanish name|Kempes|Chiodi}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Mario Alberto Kempes\n| image               = Kempes en Central.png\n| image_size          = \n| caption             = Kempes in Rosario Central in October 1975\n| fullname            = Mario Alberto Kempes Chiodi\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1954|7|15}}\n| birth_place         = [[Bell Ville]], [[Argentina]]\n| height              = {{height|m=1.84}}\n| position            = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| youthyears1         = \n| youthclubs1         = [[Instituto Atl\u00e9tico Central C\u00f3rdoba|Instituto]]\n| years1              = 1970\u20131973\n| clubs1              = [[Instituto Atl\u00e9tico Central C\u00f3rdoba|Instituto]]\n| caps1               = 13\n| goals1              = 11\n| years2              = 1973\u20131976\n| clubs2              = [[Rosario Central]]\n| caps2               = 107\n| goals2              = 85\n| years3              = 1976\u20131981\n| clubs3              = [[Valencia CF|Valencia]]\n| caps3               = 142\n| goals3              = 95\n| years4              = 1981\u20131982\n| clubs4              = [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]]\n| caps4               = 29\n| goals4              = 15\n| years5              = 1982\u20131984\n| clubs5              = [[Valencia CF|Valencia]]\n| caps5               = 42\n| goals5              = 21\n| years6              = 1984\u20131986\n| clubs6              = [[H\u00e9rcules CF|H\u00e9rcules]]\n| caps6               = 38\n| goals6              = 10\n| years7              = 1986\u20131987\n| clubs7              = [[First Vienna FC|First Vienna]]\n| caps7               = 20\n| goals7              = 7\n| years8              = 1987\u20131990\n| clubs8              = [[SKN St. P\u00f6lten|St. P\u00f6lten]]\n| caps8               = 96\n| goals8              = 34\n| years9              = 1990\u20131992\n| clubs9              = [[Kremser SC]]\n| caps9               = 39\n| goals9              = 7\n| years10             = 1992\u20131993\n| clubs10             = [[Club Deportivo Arturo Fern\u00e1ndez Vial|Fern\u00e1ndez Vial]]\n| caps10              = 11\n| goals10             = 5\n| years11             = 1993\u20131994\n| clubs11             = [[Pelita Bandung Raya|Pelita Jaya]]\n| caps11              = 18\n| goals11             = 12\n| totalcaps           = 555\n| totalgoals          = 300\n| nationalyears1      = 1973\u20131982\n| nationalteam1       = [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]]\n| nationalcaps1       = 43\n| nationalgoals1      = 20\n| manageryears1       = 1995\u20131996\n| managerclubs1       = [[Pelita Bandung Raya|Pelita Jaya]]\n| manageryears2       = 1996\n| managerclubs2       = [[KS Lushnja|Lushnja]]\n| manageryears3       = 1997\u20131998\n| managerclubs3       = [[Mineros de Guayana]]\n| manageryears4       = 1999\n| managerclubs4       = [[The Strongest]]\n| manageryears5       = 2000\n| managerclubs5       = [[Club Blooming|Blooming]]\n| manageryears6       = 2000\u20132001\n| managerclubs6       = [[Club Independiente Petrolero|Independiente Petrolero]]\n| manageryears7       = 2001\u20132002\n| managerclubs7       = [[S.S.D. Casarano Calcio]]\n|medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCountry|{{fb|ARG}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978 Argentina]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''Mario Alberto Kempes Chiodi''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8ma\u027ejo al\u02c8\u03b2e\u027eto \u02c8kempes \u02c8t\u0283jo\u00f0i}}; born 15 July 1954 in [[Bell Ville]], [[C\u00f3rdoba Province, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]]) is a retired [[Argentina|Argentine]] [[Association football|football]]er who played as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]]. His father, Mario, also a footballer, inspired him to play from a young age. At the age of seven he began playing with a junior team and at fourteen, he joined the Talleres reserves. A prolific goalscorer, at club level he is best known for playing for [[Valencia CF|Valencia]], finishing as [[La Liga]]'s [[Pichichi Trophy|top goalscorer]] twice, and amassing 116 goals in 184 league games for the club.\n\nAt international level, Kempes was the focal point of Argentina's [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978 World Cup]] win where he scored twice in the [[1978 FIFA World Cup Final|final]], and received the [[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Boot|Golden Boot]] as top goalscorer. He also won the [[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Ball|Golden Ball]] for the player of the tournament, making him one of only three players to have won all three awards at a single World Cup, along with [[Garrincha]] in 1962, and [[Paolo Rossi]] in 1982.\n\nKempes won [[South American Footballer of the Year]], [[Onze d'Or|Onze d'Or European footballer of the Year]], and [[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Ball|World Cup Golden Ball]] in 1978. In 2004, he was named as one of the [[FIFA 100|Top 125 greatest living footballers]] as part of [[FIFA]]'s 100th anniversary celebration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/3533891.stm |title=Pele's list of the greatest |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 March 2004 |accessdate=15 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n[[File:Mario Kempes River Plate.jpg|thumb|left|120px|Mario Kempes during his period in [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]], 1981]]\nKempes was nicknamed ''El Toro'' and ''El Matador''. His career started at local club [[Instituto Atl\u00e9tico Central C\u00f3rdoba|Instituto]], where he played alongside [[Osvaldo Ardiles]] before quickly moving on to [[Rosario Central]], where he scored 85 goals in 105 matches and established himself as a remarkable goalscorer, which prompted a move to [[Valencia CF]]. At [[Mestalla]] he would go on to win the [[Copa del Rey]], the [[European Cup Winners' Cup]] and the [[UEFA Super Cup]] as well as two consecutive [[Pichichi Trophy|Pichichi]]s, scoring 24 and 28 goals in 1976\u201377 and 1977\u201378 seasons. Famous as a hard-working forward, he used to strike from outside the [[penalty area]] with his surging runs towards goal and was not the traditional center-forward operating solely inside the box. Many [[Defender (association football)|defenders]] found difficulty handling his attacking style.\n\nBefore the [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978 World Cup]], Kempes was the only foreign based player on the list of coach [[C\u00e9sar Luis Menotti]]'s national team in [[Argentina]], he was at the time playing for Spanish giants [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] while the other squad members all played in Argentina. The coach described him when announcing the squad he had selected for the 1978 tournament, \"He's strong, he's got skill, he creates spaces and he shoots hard. He's a player who can make a difference, and he can play in a centre-forward position.\"\n\nKempes had been the top scorer in [[La Liga]] the previous two seasons and was determined to show on home soil that he could deliver against the best on the sport's greatest stage. However, in 1974, at the age of 20, he failed to get on the score-sheet in [[West Germany]] and after the first round group stage in 1978, his name was still missing among goal scorers in the [[tournament]].\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Mario Kempes Argentina vs. Holanda.JPG|thumb|right|180px|Kempes celebrating one of his 2 goals at the [[1978 FIFA World Cup]] final match v. Netherlands in Buenos Aires]]\nDuring his club career he won 43 caps for [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] and scored 20 times. He represented his country in three [[FIFA World Cup|World Cups]] in [[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974]], [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978]] and [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]], winning the competition in 1978. He was the [[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Boot|leading goalscorer]] in the 1978 tournament, scoring six goals in three braces: The first two in Argentina's first semifinal group stage match against Poland, another two against Peru, and the last two of these goals in the final against the Netherlands, which Argentina won 3\u20131. His second goal, in the 105th minute, was the game winner in extra time. However, in the same tournament, he notoriously stopped a goal with his hand in a second round match against Poland.<ref>Argentina vs Poland \u2013 World Cup 1978 \u2013 full match \u2013 part 4/8 @YouTube</ref> This resulted in a penalty kick that was promptly saved by [[Ubaldo Fillol]].<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=50/results/matches/match=2202/report.html FIFA.com 1978 World Cup Match Report \u2013 Argentina \u2013 Poland]</ref>\n\nIn 1978, he was named ''South American Football Player of the Year'' (\"El Mundo,\" Caracas, Venezuela). He was named by [[Pel\u00e9]] as one of the [[FIFA 100|top 125 greatest living footballers]] in March 2004.\n\n==Managerial career==\nKempes made his full-time managing debut in [[Albania]]. His brief spell with [[KS Lushnja|Lushnja]] was groundbreaking, as he became the first foreign manager who signed a foreign player for the first time in Albanian football history. His career in Albania came to a quick end in 1997. The following year, he landed a job with Venezuelan side [[Mineros de Guayana]]. In 1999, Kempes moved to Bolivia and managed [[The Strongest]], before taking charge of [[Club Blooming|Blooming]] in 2000. Previously, he worked as assistant coach for Uruguayan manager [[H\u00e9ctor N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] in [[Valencia CF|Valencia]], and as a player-manager of [[Liga Indonesia|Indonesian League]] champions [[Pelita Bandung Raya|Pelita Jaya]].\n\n==Commentary career==\nHe currently works as a football analyst and commentator in Spanish for [[ESPN Deportes]] ([[ESPN]]'s Spanish-language version). Moreover, he as well as Fernando Palomo and Ciro Procuna provide the commentary in the Latin American version of the videogames [[FIFA 13]], [[FIFA 14]], [[FIFA 15]], [[FIFA 16]], [[FIFA 17]], [[FIFA 18]], [[FIFA 19]] and [[FIFA 20]].\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Club performance\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | Cup\n! colspan=2 | League Cup\n! colspan=2 | Continental\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n! Season !! Club !! League\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n|-\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Argentina\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | Cup\n! colspan=2 | League Cup\n! colspan=2 | [[CONMEBOL|South America]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[Primera Divisi\u00f3n Argentina 1973|1973]]||[[Instituto Atl\u00e9tico Central C\u00f3rdoba|Instituto]]||[[Primera Divisi\u00f3n Argentina|Primera Divisi\u00f3n]]||13||11||||||||||||||13||11\n|-\n|[[Primera Divisi\u00f3n Argentina 1974|1974]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[Rosario Central|Central]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[Primera Divisi\u00f3n Argentina|Primera Divisi\u00f3n]]||36||29||||||||||||||36||29\n|-\n|[[Primera Divisi\u00f3n Argentina 1975|1975]]||49||35||||||||||||||49||35\n|-\n|[[Primera Divisi\u00f3n Argentina 1976|1976]]||22||21||||||||||||||22||21\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Spain\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Copa del Rey]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]]\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[1976\u201377 La Liga|1976\u201377]]||rowspan=\"5\"|[[Valencia CF|Valencia]]||rowspan=\"5\"|[[La Liga]]||34||24||0||0||-||-||-||-||34||24\n|-\n|[[1977\u201378 La Liga|1977\u201378]]||34||28||12||11||-||-||-||-||46||39\n|-\n|[[1978\u201379 La Liga|1978\u201379]]||30||12||10||3||-||-||6||3||46||18\n|-\n|[[1979\u201380 La Liga|1979\u201380]]||32||22||2||2||-||-||9||9||43||33\n|-\n|[[1980\u201381 La Liga|1980\u201381]]||12||9||1||0||-||-||5||2||18||11\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Argentina\n! colspan=2 