00f3n|Primera Divisi\u00f3n]]: [[1981 Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n|1981 Nacional]]\n\n;Pelita Jaya\n*[[Galatama]]: 1993\u201394 <ref>{{cite web|title=Indonesia&nbsp;\u2013 List of (Semi-)Professional Champions|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/indochamp.html|accessdate=18 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===International===\n;Argentina\n*[[FIFA World Cup]]: [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978]]\n\n===Individual===\n*[[List of Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n top scorers|Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n top scorers]]: [[1974 Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n|1974 Nacional]], [[1976 Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n|1976 Metropolitan]]\n*[[Pichichi Trophy]]: 1977, 1978\n*[[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Boot|FIFA World Cup Golden Boot]]: 1978\n*[[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Ball|FIFA World Cup Golden Ball]]: 1978<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/fifa-awards.html#gball |title=FIFA World Cup Golden Ball Awards |accessdate=9 February 2015 |publisher=RSSSF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112000000/http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/fifa-awards.html |archivedate=12 January 2016 }}</ref>\n*[[FIFA World Cup awards#All-Star Team|FIFA World Cup All-Star Team]]: 1978\n*[[Ballon d'Or]]: 1978 - [[Ballon d'Or#Additional awards|Le nouveau palmar\u00e8s (the new winners)]]<ref>Cr\u00e9pin, Timoth\u00e9 (2 December 2015). \"Pel\u00e9 devait \u00eatre le recordman\" (in French). France Football.</ref>\n*[[Onze d'Or]]: 1978\n*[[Player of the Year of Argentina|Olimpia de Plata]]: 1978\n*[[South American Footballer of the Year]]: 1978\n*[[List of UEFA Cup Winners' Cup top scorers|UEFA Cup Winners' Cup top scorers]]: 1979\u201380\n*[[FIFA 100]]: 2004\n*South American Player of the Century: Ranking N\u00ba 23: 2006<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/iffhs-century.html#sampoy South American \u2013 Player of the Century] Retrieved on 3 January 2009</ref>\n*[[Golden Foot]]: 2007, as football legend<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenfoot.com/en/legends/item/281-mario-kempes.html|title=Golden Foot Award|accessdate=9 February 2015|publisher=Goldenfoot.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150210035028/http://www.goldenfoot.com/en/legends/item/281-mario-kempes.html|archivedate=10 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*[[Argentine Football Association|AFA Team of All Time]] (published 2015)<ref>{{cite web |title=La Selecci\u00f3n de Todos los Tiempos |trans-title=The Team of All Time |publisher=Argentine Football Association |language=Spanish |date=4 January 2016 |url=http://www.afa.com.ar/3023/la-seleccion-de-todos-los-tiempos |accessdate=29 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180814210638/http://www.afa.com.ar/3023/la-seleccion-de-todos-los-tiempos |archive-date=14 August 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n{{cite web|website=Soccer Net USA |title=Research: Soccer Net USA |url=http://www.soccernetusa.com/mario_kempes.htm |accessdate=25 November 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116195520/http://www.soccernetusa.com/mario_kempes.htm |archivedate=16 November 2006 |url-status=dead }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons cat|Mario Kempes}}\n* {{FIFA}}\n* {{NFT}}\n* {{ESPN FC|79200|Mario Kempes}}\n* {{FootballDatabase.eu|16437|Mario Kempes}}\n* {{FootballFacts.ru|149517|Mario Kempes}}\n* {{Lequipe|13086|Mario Kempes}}\n* [http://observer.guardian.co.uk/osm/story/0,,642548,00.html Observer Sport biography]\n* {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071020024930/http://futbolfactory.futbolweb.net/index.php?ff=historicos&f2=00001&idjugador=14 |date=20 October 2007 |title=Futbol Factory profile }} {{in lang|es}}\n* {{BDFutbol|3311}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= Awards\n|bg= gold\n|fg= navy\n|bordercolor= silver\n|list1=\n{{UEFA Cup Winners' Cup top scorers}}\n{{Argentina Primera Division top scorers}}\n{{La Liga top scorers}}\n{{FIFA World Cup top scorers}}\n{{FIFA World Cup Golden Ball}}\n{{South American Footballer of the Year}}\n{{FIFA 100}}\n{{Onze Mondial European Footballer of the Year}}\n{{Argentine Footballer of the Year}}\n{{1978 FIFA World Cup Team of the Tournament}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= Argentina squads\n|bg= #6AB5FF\n|fg= white\n|bordercolor= silver\n|list1=\n{{Argentina squad 1974 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Argentina squad 1975 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Argentina squad 1978 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Argentina squad 1982 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{The Strongest managers}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kempes, Mario}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from C\u00f3rdoba Province, Argentina]]\n[[Category:Argentine footballers]]\n[[Category:Instituto footballers]]\n[[Category:River Plate footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:SKN St. P\u00f6lten players]]\n[[Category:Rosario Central footballers]]\n[[Category:Arturo Fern\u00e1ndez Vial footballers]]\n[[Category:FIFA 100]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup-winning players]]\n[[Category:1974 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:1978 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:1982 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:1975 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:Argentina international footballers]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Valencia CF players]]\n[[Category:H\u00e9rcules CF players]]\n[[Category:First Vienna FC players]]\n[[Category:Pelita Bandung Raya players]]\n[[Category:Argentine people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Argentine beach soccer players]]\n[[Category:Argentine football managers]]\n[[Category:KS Lushnja managers]]\n[[Category:Mineros de Guayana managers]]\n[[Category:The Strongest managers]]\n[[Category:Club Blooming managers]]\n[[Category:Pichichi Trophy winners]]\n[[Category:Primera B de Chile players]]\n[[Category:Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Austrian Football Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Chile]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate sportspeople in Chile]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate sportspeople in Austria]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Austria]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:South American Footballer of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Albania]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Venezuela]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Move place of birth out of lede per Manuel of Style. Minor corrections.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mario_Kempes"}
{"title_page": "Louis the Younger", "text_new": "{{about||the king of France known as Louis the Younger|Louis VII of France|the emperor of that name|Louis II of Italy}}\n{{Infobox monarch\n|image           = Treaty of Fouron.jpg\n|reign           = King of Saxony: 876\u2013882<br />King of Bavaria: 880-882\n|coronation      =\n|full name       =\n|predecessor     = [[Louis the German|Louis II]] as King of East Francia\n|successor       = [[Charles the Fat|Charles III]]\n|spouse          = [[Liutgard of Saxony (died 885)|Liutgard of Saxony]]\n|issue           = [[Hugh of Saxony|Hugh]]<br />Louis<br />Bernhard<br />Hildegard\n|royal house     = [[Carolingian]]\n|father          = [[Louis the German|Louis II]]\n|mother          = [[Hemma|Emma of Altdorf]]\n|birth_date      = 830 or 835\n|birth_place     =\n|death_date      = 20 January 882\n|death_place     = [[Frankfurt]], [[East Francia]]\n|place of burial = [[Lorsch Abbey]]\n|succession      = [[King of Saxony]]\n}}\n'''Louis the Younger''' (830/835 \u2013 20 January 882), sometimes '''Louis III''',<ref>[[Louis the Pious]] and [[Louis the German]] would be Louis I and Louis II, respectively, in this numbering. If counted as \"Louis III of Germany,\" he should not be confused with [[Louis III, Holy Roman Emperor]], or [[Louis the Child]]. He may also be counted as \"Louis II.\"</ref> was the second eldest of the three sons of [[Louis the German]] and [[Hemma|Emma]].{{sfn|McKitterick|1999|p=354}} He succeeded his father as the [[King of Saxony]] on 28 August 876 and his elder brother [[Carloman of Bavaria|Carloman]] as [[King of Bavaria]] from 880 to 882. He died in 882 and was succeeded in all his territories, which encompassed most of [[East Francia]], by his younger brother, [[Charles the Fat]], already [[king of Italy]] and [[Carolingian emperor|emperor]].\n\n==Military youth==\nAs a young man, Louis was deployed in military operations against the [[Abodrites]] to the east in 858 and 862.<ref>Reuter, 72.</ref> In 854, at the invitation of the nobles of [[Aquitaine]] opposed to [[Charles the Bald]] and [[Pepin II of Aquitaine|Pepin II]], and coaxed by his father and his cousin [[Charles, Archbishop of Mainz]], he crossed into Gaul at the head of an army, intent on receiving the Aquitainian crown. He marched as far as [[Limoges]] before turning back.\n\nBack home, Louis forged close ties with the nobles of East Francia and became increasingly independent from his father. He engaged himself to the daughter of Count Adalard and, in 865, he and his brother Charles joined in rebellion against their father. This flirtation with revolt was brief, however, and Louis, Charles, and their father were reconciled later that year, though the elder Louis was forced to make a division of the remainder of his territories between his two sons. Carloman had already been given the ''[[Subkingdom (Monarchy)|subregulus]]'' of [[Bavaria]] in 864, now Louis received [[Saxony]], [[Thuringia]], and [[Franconia]] and Charles [[Alemannia]] and [[Rhaetia]].\n\nIn 869, Louis married [[Liutgard of Saxony (died 885)|Liutgard of Saxony]], daughter of [[Liudolf, Duke of Saxony]], at [[Aschaffenburg]]. Liutgard was a strong-willed and politically ambitious woman and later on spurred her husband to pursue ambitious goals. This match increased tensions between father and son and in 871 and in 873, Louis rebelled, but, on each occasion, he later reconciled with his father.\n\n==Rule in Saxony==\nUpon his father's death in 876, Louis fully inherited his subkingdoms, bearing the title ''rex Francorum'' (\"king of the Franks\"). Louis the Younger considered himself the true heir of Louis the German and as his father died in 876, Louis buried him in the abbey of [[Lorsch]], in his own territories, in order to emphasise his primacy to his brothers. Louis also retained his father's chief advisor, [[Liutbert, Archbishop of Mainz|Liutbert]], [[Archbishop of Mainz]]. He and his brother ruled their kingdoms independently but cooperatively and never at war.\n\n===Acquisition of Lotharingia and Bavaria===\nLouis's rule was immediately threatened by Charles the Bald, who tried to annex the eastern parts of [[Lotharingia]] and maybe even to achieve supremacy over his nephew. Louis brought war on Charles and, on 8 October 876 at [[Andernach]], he defeated the much-larger host of West Francia. The East Frankish army displayed superiority in both unity and tactics, and the young king had even dressed his soldiers in white garments so that they appeared as an army of spirits.\n\nAfter this victory, Louis the German's three sons met in November at [[N\u00f6rdlingen]] to discuss the division of their father's kingdom and to have their hosts swear allegiance. According to the plan drawn up in 865, which their father, despite all his sons' rebellions, had confirmed in 872, Carloman received Bavaria, Charles Swabia, and Louis Saxony, Franconia, and Thuringia. Throughout his reign, though he is always called \"King of Saxony\" by historians, he never visited Saxony proper, though it formed the bulk of his territory. At the end of 877, the brothers assembled again to discuss the administration of their half of Lotharingia. After Carloman relinquished his claim, the realm was divided between Louis and Charles, who again met in September 878 in [[Alsace|Alsatia]]. In 879, Carloman was incapacitated by a stroke and named Louis as his successor (and erstwhile regent) in Bavaria. Louis received it outright a year later when Carloman expired.\n\nIn November 878 after the death of Charles the Bald, his heir, [[Louis the Stammerer]], and the latter's cousin Louis the Younger promised each other to respect the succession of their respective sons and to issue no claims contrary to that, at [[Voeren]] (''Fourons'' in [[French language|French]]). This Treaty of Fouron was soon put to the test, when Louis the Stammerer died in April 879. A party of western nobles led by [[Abbot Joscelin]] invited Louis the Younger to succeed to the rule of the western kingdom. Since his wife Liutgard also advocated heeding this call, Louis invaded West Francia. He marched as far as [[Verdun]], but after the new kings [[Louis III of France|Louis III]] and [[Carloman of France|Carloman]] ceded their part of [[Lotharingia]] to the invader, Louis retreated. In February 880, this gain was confirmed by the [[Treaty of Ribemont]], signed near [[Saint-Quentin, Aisne|Saint Quentin]]. This treaty determined the border of the two kingdoms, which was to remain unchanged until the fourteenth century.\n\n===Relationship with the nobility===\nIn contrast to his father, Louis the Younger preferred reconciling royal interests with those of the nobility and avoided confrontation. He managed to bind powerful families to the king, including the [[Ottonian|Liudovingian]] relatives of his wife, that later themselves became kings and emperors. Louis mostly stayed in the [[Rhineland]], avoiding Saxony or his eastern borders. Louis did visit Bavaria on two occasions, but mostly left it to the government of his illegitimate nephew, Carloman's son, [[Arnulf of Carinthia|Arnulf]], [[Duke of Carinthia]].<ref>As \"prefect of the marches.\" Bowlus, 569.</ref>\n\n===Viking incursions===\nSince the summer of 879, [[Vikings]] had been increasing their attacks on the Frankish kingdom and occasionally penetrated deeply into the interior of the land. Louis's kingdom was the most hard-hit after that of West Francia. In February 880, Louis confronted and defeated a [[Norsemen|Norse]] host at the [[Battle of Thimeon]] (near modern [[Charleroi]]).{{sfn|McKitterick|1995|p=234-235}} His son Hugh, however, was killed in this battle.{{sfn|McKitterick|1995|p=234-235}} The next year, Louis defeated the [[Norsemen|Norse]] again at the [[Battle of Saucourt-en-Vimeu|battle of Saucourt]].{{sfn|McKitterick|1999|p=235}} Louis also drove the Norse out of the royal palace of [[Nijmegen]], which they had occupied. In the same month, a Saxon host commanded by [[Brun, Duke of Saxony|Duke Bruno]], the king's brother-in-law, suffered a heavy defeat near [[Hamburg]] and Bruno and many other Saxon nobles fell.\n\n==Death and succession==\nLouis fell sick in 881 and died in [[Frankfurt]] on 20 January 882. He was buried beside his father in the abbey of Lorsch. By his wife Liutgard of Saxony, he had had a son called Louis (877&ndash;879), who died in a fall from a palace window, and a daughter called Hildegard (878&ndash;895). Louis had also fathered an illegitimate son, Hugh (855/60 \u2013 February 880), either with the daughter of Adalard or with an earlier concubine. Since he left no heir, all his territories fell to his brother Charles, who thus could reunite the entire East Frankish kingdom. Hildegard later joined with the Bavarian magnate [[Engeldeo]] in conspiring against [[Arnulf of Carinthia|King Arnulf]] and was deprived of her \"public honours\" in 895, according to the ''[[Annals of Fulda]]''.\n\n== Family ==\nLouis the Younger married Liutgard, a daughter of Duke [[Liudolf, Duke of Saxony|Liudolf of Saxony]], who was grandfather of King [[Henry I of Germany]].\n\n* [[Louis of Saxony|Louis]] (876 - November 879)\n* Hildegard (875/878 or 881 - after ca.900)\n* Bernhart\n\nHis illegitimate children were:\n* [[Hugo (Son of Louis the Younger)|Hugo]] (ca. 855/860 - February 880), illegitimate son{{sfn|McKitterick|1995|p=234-235}}\n* Adalhard, illegitimate son\n\n==See also==\n*[[Kings of Germany family tree]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*[[Charles Oman|Oman, Charles]]. ''The Dark Ages 476&ndash;918''. London: Rivingtons, 1914.\n*{{cite book |title=The Carolingians and the Written Word |first=Rosamond |last=McKitterick |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1995 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |title=The Frankish Kingdoms under the Carolingians |first=Rosamond |last=McKitterick |publisher=Pearson Education Limited |year=1999 |ref=harv}}\n*Bowlus, Charles R. \"[https://www.jstor.org/stable/2846382 Imre Boba's Reconsiderations of Moravia's Early History and Arnulf of Carinthia's Ostpolitik (887-892).] ''Speculum'', Vol. 62, No. 3. (Jul., 1987), pp 552\u2013574.\n*[[Reuter, Timothy]]. ''Germany in the Early Middle Ages, c. 800&ndash;1056''. Longman, 1991.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100226063634/http://www.medievalsources.co.uk/fulda.htm ''Annales Fuldenses'' translated by Timothy Reuter, with commentary (subscription needed).]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.tacitus.nu/historical-atlas/francia2.htm The Dissolution of the Frankish Empire at Historical Atlas.] Good for maps of Louis's realm and his brothers'.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Carolingian|Carolingian Dynasty]]||830/835|20 January|882|name=Louis III}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Louis the German]]|as=king of East Francia}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[King of Saxony]]|years=876 \u2013882}}\n{{s-aft|rows=4|after=[[Charles the Fat]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Carloman of Bavaria|Carloman]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[King of Bavaria]]|years=880\u2013882}}\n|-\n{{s-vac|last=[[Lothair II]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[King of Lotharingia]]|years=880\u2013882}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Charles the Fat]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Duke of Swabia]]|years=880\u2013882}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Carolingians footer}}\n{{German monarchs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Louis the Younger}}\n[[Category:830s births]]\n[[Category:882 deaths]]\n[[Category:9th-century kings of East Francia]]\n[[Category:9th-century rulers of Bavaria]]\n[[Category:Kings of Bavaria]]\n[[Category:Kings of Saxony]]\n[[Category:Kings of Lotharingia]]\n[[Category:Dukes of Swabia]]\n[[Category:Frankish warriors]]\n[[Category:Burials at Lorsch Abbey]]\n[[Category:Thuringii]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the king of France known as Louis the Younger|Louis VII of France|the emperor of that name|Louis II of Italy}}\n{{Infobox monarch\n|image           = Treaty of Fouron.jpg\n|reign           = King of Saxony: 876\u2013882<br />King of Bavaria: 880-882\n|coronation      =\n|full name       =\n|predecessor     = [[Louis the German|Louis II]] as King of East Francia\n|successor       = [[Charles the Fat|Charles III]]\n|spouse          = [[Liutgard of Saxony (died 885)|Liutgard of Saxony]]\n|issue           = [[Hugh of Saxony|Hugh]]<br />Louis<br />Bernhard<br />Hildegard\n|royal house     = [[Carolingian]]\n|father          = [[Louis the German|Louis II]]\n|mother          = [[Hemma|Emma of Altdorf]]\n|birth_date      = 830 or 835\n|birth_place     =\n|death_date      = 20 January 882\n|death_place     = [[Frankfurt]], [[East Francia]]\n|place of burial = [[Lorsch Abbey]]\n|succession      = [[King of Saxony]]\n}}\n'''Louis the Younger''' (830/835 \u2013 20 January 882), sometimes '''Louis III''',<ref>[[Louis the Pious]] and [[Louis the German]] would be Louis I and Louis II, respectively, in this numbering. If counted as \"Louis III of Germany,\" he should not be confused with [[Louis III, Holy Roman Emperor]], or [[Louis the Child]]. He may also be counted as \"Louis II.\"</ref> was the second eldest of the three sons of [[Louis the German]] and [[Hemma|Emma]].{{sfn|McKitterick|1999|p=354}} He succeeded his father as the [[King of Saxony]] on 28 August 876 and his elder brother [[Carloman of Bavaria|Carloman]] as [[King of Bavaria]] from 880 to 882. He died in 882 and was succeeded in all his territories, which encompassed most of [[East Francia]], by his younger brother, [[Charles the Fat]], already [[king of Italy]] and [[Carolingian emperor|emperor]].\n\n==Military youth==\nAs a young man, Louis was deployed in military operations against the [[Abodrites]] to the east in 858 and 862.<ref>Reuter, 72.</ref> In 854, at the invitation of the nobles of [[Aquitaine]] opposed to [[Charles the Bald]] and [[Pepin II of Aquitaine|Pepin II]], and coaxed by his father and his cousin [[Charles, Archbishop of Mainz]], he crossed into Gaul at the head of an army, intent on receiving the Aquitainian crown. He marched as far as [[Limoges]] before turning back.\n\nBack home, Louis forged close ties with the nobles of East Francia and became increasingly independent from his father. He engaged himself to the daughter of Count Adalard and, in 865, he and his brother Charles joined in rebellion against their father. This flirtation with revolt was brief, however, and Louis, Charles, and their father were reconciled later that year, though the elder Louis was forced to make a division of the remainder of his territories between his two sons. Carloman had already been given the ''[[Subkingdom (Monarchy)|subregulus]]'' of [[Bavaria]] in 864, now Louis received [[Saxony]], [[Thuringia]], and [[Franconia]] and Charles [[Alemannia]] and [[Rhaetia]].\n\nIn 869, Louis married [[Liutgard of Saxony (died 885)|Liutgard of Saxony]], daughter of [[Liudolf, Duke of Saxony]], at [[Aschaffenburg]]. Liutgard was a strong-willed and politically ambitious woman and later on spurred her husband to pursue ambitious goals. This match increased tensions between father and son and in 871 and in 873, Louis rebelled, but, on each occasion, he later reconciled with his father.\n\n==Rule in Saxony==\nUpon his father's death in 876, Louis fully inherited his subkingdoms, bearing the title ''rex Francorum'' (\"king of the Franks\"). Louis the Younger considered himself the true heir of Louis the German and as his father died in 876, Louis buried him in the abbey of [[Lorsch]], in his own territories, in order to emphasise his primacy to his brothers. Louis also retained his father's chief advisor, [[Liutbert, Archbishop of Mainz|Liutbert]], [[Archbishop of Mainz]]. He and his brother ruled their kingdoms independently but cooperatively and never at war.\n\n===Acquisition of Lotharingia and Bavaria===\nLouis's rule was immediately threatened by Charles the Bald, who tried to annex the eastern parts of [[Lotharingia]] and maybe even to achieve supremacy over his nephew. Louis brought war on Charles and, on 8 October 876 at [[Andernach]], he defeated the much-larger host of West Francia. The East Frankish army displayed superiority in both unity and tactics, and the young king had even dressed his soldiers in white garments so that they appeared as an army of spirits.\n\nAfter this victory, Louis the German's three sons met in November at [[N\u00f6rdlingen]] to discuss the division of their father's kingdom and to have their hosts swear allegiance. According to the plan drawn up in 865, which their father, despite all his sons' rebellions, had confirmed in 872, Carloman received Bavaria, Charles Swabia, and Louis Saxony, Franconia, and Thuringia. Throughout his reign, though he is always called \"King of Saxony\" by historians, he never visited Saxony proper, though it formed the bulk of his territory. At the end of 877, the brothers assembled again to discuss the administration of their half of Lotharingia. After Carloman relinquished his claim, the realm was divided between Louis and Charles, who again met in September 878 in [[Alsace|Alsatia]]. In 879, Carloman was incapacitated by a stroke and named Louis as his successor (and erstwhile regent) in Bavaria. Louis received it outright a year later when Carloman expired.\n\nIn November 878 after the death of Charles the Bald, his heir, [[Louis the Stammerer]], and the latter's cousin Louis the Younger promised each other to respect the succession of their respective sons and to issue no claims contrary to that, at [[Voeren]] (''Fourons'' in [[French language|French]]). This Treaty of Fouron was soon put to the test, when Louis the Stammerer died in April 879. A party of western nobles led by [[Abbot Joscelin]] invited Louis the Younger to succeed to the rule of the western kingdom. Since his wife Liutgard also advocated heeding this call, Louis invaded West Francia. He marched as far as [[Verdun]], but after the new kings [[Louis III of France|Louis III]] and [[Carloman of France|Carloman]] ceded their part of [[Lotharingia]] to the invader, Louis retreated. In February 880, this gain was confirmed by the [[Treaty of Ribemont]], signed near [[Saint-Quentin, Aisne|Saint Quentin]]. This treaty determined the border of the two kingdoms, which was to remain unchanged until the fourteenth century.\n\n===Relationship with the nobility===\nIn contrast to his father, Louis the Younger preferred reconciling royal interests with those of the nobility and avoided confrontation. He managed to bind powerful families to the king, including the [[Ottonian|Liudovingian]] relatives of his wife, that later themselves became kings and emperors. Louis mostly stayed in the [[Rhineland]], avoiding Saxony or his eastern borders. Louis did visit Bavaria on two occasions, but mostly left it to the government of his illegitimate nephew, Carloman's son, [[Arnulf of Carinthia|Arnulf]], [[Duke of Carinthia]].<ref>As \"prefect of the marches.\" Bowlus, 569.</ref>\n\n===Viking incursions===\nSince the summer of 879, [[Vikings]] had been increasing their attacks on the Frankish kingdom and occasionally penetrated deeply into the interior of the land. Louis's kingdom was the most hard-hit after that of West Francia. In February 880, Louis confronted and defeated a [[Norsemen|Norse]] host at the [[Battle of Thimeon]] (near modern [[Charleroi]]).{{sfn|McKitterick|1995|p=234-235}} His son Hugh, however, was killed in this battle.{{sfn|McKitterick|1995|p=234-235}} The next year, Louis defeated the [[Norsemen|Norse]] again at the [[Battle of Saucourt-en-Vimeu|battle of Saucourt]].{{sfn|McKitterick|1999|p=235}} Louis also drove the Norse out of the royal palace of [[Nijmegen]], which they had occupied. In the same month, a Saxon host commanded by [[Brun, Duke of Saxony|Duke Bruno]], the king's brother-in-law, suffered a heavy defeat near [[Hamburg]] and Bruno and many other Saxon nobles fell.\n\n==Death and succession==\nLouis fell sick in 881 and died in [[Frankfurt]] on 20 January 882. He was buried beside his father in the abbey of Lorsch. By his wife Liutgard of Saxony, he had had a son called Louis (877&ndash;879), who died in a fall from a palace window, and a daughter called Hildegard (878&ndash;895). Louis had also fathered an illegitimate son, Hugh (855/60 \u2013 February 880), either with the daughter of Adalard or with an earlier concubine. Since he left no heir, all his territories fell to his brother Charles, who thus could reunite the entire East Frankish kingdom. Hildegard later joined with the Bavarian magnate [[Engeldeo]] in conspiring against [[Arnulf of Carinthia|King Arnulf]] and was deprived of her \"public honours\" in 895, according to the ''[[Annals of Fulda]]''.\n\n== Family ==\nLouis the Younger married Liutgard, a daughter of Duke [[Liudolf, Duke of Saxony|Liudolf of Saxony]], Liudolf of Saxony was grandfather of King [[Henry I of Germany]].\n\n* [[Louis of Saxony|Louis]] (876 - November 879)\n* Hildegard (875/878 or 881 - after ca.900)\n* Bernhart\n\nHis illegitimate children were:\n* [[Hugo (Son of Louis the Younger)|Hugo]] (ca. 855/860 - February 880), illegitimate son{{sfn|McKitterick|1995|p=234-235}}\n* Adalhard, illegitimate son\n\n==See also==\n*[[Kings of Germany family tree]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*[[Charles Oman|Oman, Charles]]. ''The Dark Ages 476&ndash;918''. London: Rivingtons, 1914.\n*{{cite book |title=The Carolingians and the Written Word |first=Rosamond |last=McKitterick |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1995 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |title=The Frankish Kingdoms under the Carolingians |first=Rosamond |last=McKitterick |publisher=Pearson Education Limited |year=1999 |ref=harv}}\n*Bowlus, Charles R. \"[https://www.jstor.org/stable/2846382 Imre Boba's Reconsiderations of Moravia's Early History and Arnulf of Carinthia's Ostpolitik (887-892).] ''Speculum'', Vol. 62, No. 3. (Jul., 1987), pp 552\u2013574.\n*[[Reuter, Timothy]]. ''Germany in the Early Middle Ages, c. 800&ndash;1056''. Longman, 1991.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100226063634/http://www.